### Enums in Rust

Enums (enumerations) define a type by enumerating its possible variants. Each variant can optionally carry data.

---

### Enum Variants

| Form | Example |
|------|---------|
| No data | `enum Color { Red, Green, Blue }` |
| With data | `enum IpAddr { V4(u8, u8, u8, u8), V6(String) }` |
| With struct | `enum Message { Quit, Move { x: i32, y: i32 } }` |

---

### Examples

```rust
// Simple enum
enum Direction {
    Up,
    Down,
    Left,
    Right,
}

// Enum with associated data
#[derive(Debug)]
enum IpAddrKind {
    V4(u8, u8, u8, u8),
    V6(String),
}

let home = IpAddrKind::V4(127, 0, 0, 1);
let loopback = IpAddrKind::V6(String::from("::1"));

// Enum with different variant types
enum Message {
    Quit,                       // no data
    Move { x: i32, y: i32 },    // anonymous struct
    Write(String),              // tuple struct
    ChangeColor(i32, i32, i32), // tuple
}
```

> **Key Point:** Enums in Rust are powerful algebraic data types. Each variant can hold different types and amounts of data. Combined with `match`, enums enable expressive and safe code.

codeExample:
#[derive(Debug)]
enum Coin {
    Penny,
    Nickel,
    Dime,
    Quarter,
}

fn value_in_cents(coin: Coin) -> u8 {
    match coin {
        Coin::Penny => 1,
        Coin::Nickel => 5,
        Coin::Dime => 10,
        Coin::Quarter => 25,
    }
}

fn main() {
    let coin = Coin::Quarter;
    println!("Value: {} cents", value_in_cents(coin));
}
